{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Organizing Clusters as a Hierarchical Tree\n","\n","**Hierarchical clustering** is an alternative approach to prototype-based clustering algorithms like k-means. One of its main advantages is that it allows us to plot **dendrograms** (visualizations of a binary hierarchical clustering), which can help with the interpretation of the results by creating meaningful taxonomies. Another advantage is that we do not need to specify the number of clusters upfront.\n","\n","There are two main approaches to hierarchical clustering:\n","\n","1. **Divisive hierarchical clustering:** Starts with one cluster encompassing all our samples, and we iteratively split the cluster into smaller clusters until each cluster contains only one sample.\n","2. **Agglomerative hierarchical clustering:** Takes the opposite approach. We start with each sample as an individual cluster and merge the closest pairs of clusters until only one cluster remains.\n","\n","## Agglomerative Clustering: Single vs. Complete Linkage\n","\n","The two most standard algorithms for agglomerative clustering are:\n","\n","* **Single linkage:** Computes the distances between the most similar members for each pair of clusters and merges the two clusters where the distance between the most similar members is the smallest.\n","* **Complete linkage:** Instead of comparing the most similar members, we compare the most dissimilar members to perform the merge.\n","\n","### Steps for Agglomerative Clustering (Complete Linkage)\n","\n","1. Compute the distance matrix of all data points.\n","2. Represent each data point as a single-item cluster.\n","3. Merge the two closest clusters based on the distance between the most dissimilar (distant) members.\n","4. Update the similarity (distance) matrix.\n","5. Repeat steps 2-4 until one single cluster remains.\n","\n","---"],"metadata":{"id":"9iGh_7pYOAyv"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 1. Generating a Sample Dataset\n","\n","First, let's generate some random sample data to work with. We will create 5 random data points consisting of 3 features (X, Y, Z)."],"metadata":{"id":"VZlk18rBPA3L"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import pandas as pd\n","import numpy as np\n","\n","# Set seed for reproducibility\n","np.random.seed(123)\n","\n","variables = ['X', 'Y', 'Z']\n","labels = ['ID_0', 'ID_1', 'ID_2', 'ID_3', 'ID_4']\n","\n","# Generate random data\n","X = np.random.random_sample([5, 3]) * 10\n","df = pd.DataFrame(X, columns=variables, index=labels)\n","\n","print(\"Generated DataFrame:\")\n","print(df)"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Generated DataFrame:\n","             X         Y         Z\n","ID_0  6.964692  2.861393  2.268515\n","ID_1  5.513148  7.194690  4.231065\n","ID_2  9.807642  6.848297  4.809319\n","ID_3  3.921175  3.431780  7.290497\n","ID_4  4.385722  0.596779  3.980443\n"]}],"execution_count":1,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"opB94V8AOAyy","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1782918505011,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":477,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"80114999-7157-4caa-be78-081f8b532354"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 2. Calculating the Distance Matrix\n","\n","To calculate the distance matrix for hierarchical clustering, we use the `pdist` (pairwise distances) function from SciPy to compute the Euclidean distance between our points."],"metadata":{"id":"th4VH_9iOAyz"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist, squareform\n","\n","# Calculate the symmetric distance matrix\n","row_dist = pd.DataFrame(squareform(pdist(df, metric='euclidean')),\n","                        columns=labels,\n","                        index=labels)\n","\n","print(\"\\nDistance Matrix:\")\n","print(row_dist)"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["\n","Distance Matrix:\n","          ID_0      ID_1      ID_2      ID_3      ID_4\n","ID_0  0.000000  4.973534  5.516653  5.899885  3.835396\n","ID_1  4.973534  0.000000  4.347073  5.104311  6.698233\n","ID_2  5.516653  4.347073  0.000000  7.244262  8.316594\n","ID_3  5.899885  5.104311  7.244262  0.000000  4.382864\n","ID_4  3.835396  6.698233  8.316594  4.382864  0.000000\n"]}],"execution_count":2,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"EoZ4vb0POAy0","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1782918505369,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":360,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"0096ec35-1c4b-4151-e89c-f0639b510396"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 3. Applying the Linkage Function\n","\n","Next, we apply the complete linkage agglomeration algorithm using SciPy's `linkage` function.\n","\n","*Note: It is a common mistake to pass a squareform distance matrix to `linkage`. You must pass either the **condensed distance matrix** (from `pdist`) or the **original data array**.*"],"metadata":{"id":"_IK7zj_0OAy0"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import linkage\n","\n","# CORRECT APPROACH 1: Pass the condensed distance matrix\n","row_clusters = linkage(pdist(df, metric='euclidean'), method='complete')\n","\n","# CORRECT APPROACH 2: Pass the original data array (results in the same matrix)\n","# row_clusters = linkage(df.values, method='complete', metric='euclidean')\n","\n","# Convert the linkage matrix to a DataFrame for readability\n","linkage_df = pd.DataFrame(row_clusters,\n","             columns=['row label 1', 'row label 2', 'distance', 'no. of items in clust.'],\n","             index=[f'cluster {i + 1}' for i in range(row_clusters.shape[0])])\n","\n","print(\"\\nLinkage Matrix:\")\n","print(linkage_df)"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["\n","Linkage Matrix:\n","           row label 1  row label 2  distance  no. of items in clust.\n","cluster 1          0.0          4.0  3.835396                     2.0\n","cluster 2          1.0          2.0  4.347073                     2.0\n","cluster 3          3.0          5.0  5.899885                     3.0\n","cluster 4          6.0          7.0  8.316594                     5.0\n"]}],"execution_count":3,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"yR-5oQaAOAy1","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1782918505461,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":80,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"84127bcf-7c3f-46f3-ce91-d98f12895bc9"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 4. Visualizing the Dendrogram\n","\n","We can visualize the linkage matrix as a dendrogram to understand how the clusters were merged."],"metadata":{"id":"gq3iKGMdOAy1"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram\n","\n","plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\n","# Plot the dendrogram\n","row_dendr = dendrogram(row_clusters, labels=labels)\n","\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.ylabel('Euclidean distance')\n","plt.title('Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram')\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 800x500 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":4,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":529},"id":"4avxVpnNOAy1","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1782918505940,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":466,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"f4844c25-4d51-463e-fa4a-9d446ded4cfb"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 5. Attaching Dendrograms to a Heatmap\n","\n","A common and powerful visualization is combining a dendrogram with a heatmap of the original data. This requires reordering the rows of the DataFrame to match the cluster leaves."],"metadata":{"id":"v49YtwKROAy2"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# 1. Create a new figure object and define axes for the dendrogram\n","fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8), facecolor='white')\n","axd = fig.add_axes([0.09, 0.1, 0.2, 0.6])\n","\n","# 2. Rotate the dendrogram 90 degrees\n","row_dendr = dendrogram(row_clusters, orientation='left')\n","\n","# 3. Reorder the data with respect to the clustering\n","df_rowclust = df.iloc[row_dendr['leaves'][::-1]]\n","\n","# 4. Remove ticks and spines from the dendrogram axes\n","axd.set_xticks([])\n","axd.set_yticks([])\n","for i in axd.spines.values():\n","    i.set_visible(False)\n","\n","# 5. Add the heatmap\n","axm = fig.add_axes([0.23, 0.1, 0.6, 0.6])  # x-pos, y-pos, width, height\n","cax = axm.matshow(df_rowclust, interpolation='nearest', cmap='hot_r')\n","\n","# 6. Add colorbar and format labels\n","fig.colorbar(cax)\n","axm.set_xticklabels([''] + list(df_rowclust.columns))\n","axm.set_yticklabels([''] + list(df_rowclust.index))\n","\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stderr","text":["/tmp/ipykernel_2166/2747211916.py:23: UserWarning: set_ticklabels() should only be used with a fixed number of ticks, i.e. after set_ticks() or using a FixedLocator.\n","  axm.set_xticklabels([''] + list(df_rowclust.columns))\n","/tmp/ipykernel_2166/2747211916.py:24: UserWarning: set_ticklabels() should only be used with a fixed number of ticks, i.e. after set_ticks() or using a FixedLocator.\n","  axm.set_yticklabels([''] + list(df_rowclust.index))\n"]},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 800x800 with 3 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":5,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":614},"id":"vzYl28qnOAy2","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1782918506502,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":559,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"8d049ba5-b378-4051-b3f9-967db77157b6"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 6. Agglomerative Clustering in Scikit-Learn\n","\n","While SciPy is great for plotting and distance matrices, you can also perform hierarchical clustering directly using Scikit-Learn. This is particularly useful if you want to integrate the clustering step into an existing machine learning pipeline."],"metadata":{"id":"iNSdOYOjOAy2"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering\n","\n","# Initialize with 3 clusters\n","ac = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3,\n","                             metric='euclidean',\n","                             linkage='complete')\n","labels = ac.fit_predict(X)\n","print(f'Cluster labels (k=3): {labels}')\n","\n","# Re-run with 2 clusters to see how it groups the final branches\n","ac2 = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=2,\n","                              metric='euclidean',\n","                              linkage='complete')\n","labels2 = ac2.fit_predict(X)\n","print(f'Cluster labels (k=2): {labels2}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Cluster labels (k=3): [1 0 0 2 1]\n","Cluster labels (k=2): [0 1 1 0 0]\n"]}],"execution_count":7,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"2urZFrqaOAy2","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1782918586198,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":19,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"05570b6e-3abe-4908-b6ed-661604784ab5"}}],"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}